# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: control-flow-analysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] In compiler construction, a **basic block** is a straight-line code sequence with no branches in except to the entry and no branches out except at the exit.
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] This restricted form makes a basic block highly amenable to analysis.
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] Compilers usually decompose programs into their basic blocks as a first step in the analysis process.
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] Basic blocks form the vertices or nodes in a control-flow graph.
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] Under these circumstances, whenever the first instruction in a basic block is executed, the rest of the instructions are necessarily executed exactly once and in order.
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] The code may be source code, assembly code, or some other sequence of instructions.
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] This definition is more general than the intuitive one in some ways.
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] For example, it allows unconditional jumps to labels not targeted by other jumps.
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] This definition embodies the properties that make basic blocks easy to work with when constructing an algorithm.
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] The blocks to which control may transfer after reaching the end of a block are called that block's *successors*, while the blocks from which control may have come when entering a block are called that block's *predecessors*.
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] The start of a basic block may be jumped to from more than one location.
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] The algorithm for generating basic blocks from a listing of code is simple: the analyser scans over the code, marking *block boundaries*, which are instructions that may either begin or end a block because they either transfer control or accept control from another point.
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] Then, the listing is simply "cut" at each of these points, and basic blocks remain.
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] Note that this method does not always generate *maximal* basic blocks, by the formal definition, but they are usually sufficient (maximal basic blocks are basic blocks that cannot be extended by including adjacent blocks without violating the definition of a basic block).
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] The target of a conditional or an unconditional goto/jump instruction is a leader.
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] The instruction that immediately follows a conditional or an unconditional goto/jump instruction is a leader.
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] Starting from a leader, the set of all following instructions until and not including the next leader is the basic block corresponding to the starting leader.
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] Note that, because control can never pass through the end of a basic block, some instructions may have to be modified to find the basic blocks.
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] In particular, fall-through conditional branches must be changed to two-way branches, and function calls throwing exceptions must have unconditional jumps added after them.
[src:control-flow-analysis/basic-block] Doing these may require adding labels to the beginning of other blocks.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] A **call graph** (also known as a **call multigraph**) is a control-flow graph, which represents calling relationships between subroutines in a computer program.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] Each node represents a procedure and each edge *(f, g)* indicates that procedure *f* calls procedure *g*.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] Thus, a cycle in the graph indicates recursive procedure calls.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] A dynamic call graph is a record of an execution of the program, for example as output by a profiler.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] Thus, a dynamic call graph can be exact, but only describes one run of the program.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] A static call graph is a call graph intended to represent every possible run of the program.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] The exact static call graph is an undecidable problem, so static call graph algorithms are generally overapproximations.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] That is, every call relationship that occurs is represented in the graph, and possibly also some call relationships that would never occur in actual runs of the program.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] Call graphs can be defined to represent varying degrees of precision.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] A more precise call graph more precisely approximates the behavior of the real program, at the cost of taking longer to compute and more memory to store.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] The most precise call graph is fully *context-sensitive*, which means that for each procedure, the graph contains a separate node for each call stack that procedure can be activated with.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] A fully context-sensitive call graph is called a calling context tree.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] This can be computed dynamically easily, although it may take up a large amount of memory.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] Calling context trees are usually not computed statically, because it would take too long for a large program.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] The least precise call graph is *context-insensitive*, which means that there is only one node for each procedure.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] With languages that feature dynamic dispatch (e.g.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] Java or C++), first-class functions (e.g.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] Python or Racket), or function pointers (e.g.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] C), computing a static call graph precisely requires alias analysis results.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] Conversely, computing precise aliasing requires a call graph.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] Many static analysis systems solve the apparent infinite regress by computing both simultaneously.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] Call graphs can be used in different ways.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] One simple application of call graphs is finding procedures that are never called.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] Call graphs can act as documentation for humans to understand programs.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] Call graphs can also be used to detect anomalies of program execution or code injection attacks.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] Static and dynamic analysis engines for both host and embedded software, with a myriad of reports including call graphs.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] Turns a text representation of any graph (including a call graph) into a picture.
[src:control-flow-analysis/call-graph] Command-line utility that performs a topological sort.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-analysis] In computer science, **control-flow analysis** (**CFA**) is a static-code-analysis technique for determining the control flow of a program.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-analysis] The control flow is expressed as a control-flow graph (CFG).
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-analysis] For both functional programming languages and object-oriented programming languages, the term CFA, and elaborations such as *k*-CFA, refer to specific algorithms that compute control flow.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-analysis] For many imperative programming languages, the control flow of a program is explicit in a program's source code.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-analysis] As a result, interprocedural control-flow analysis implicitly usually refers to a static analysis technique for determining the receivers of function or method calls in computer programs written in a higher-order programming language.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-analysis] it is unclear to which procedure `f` may refer.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-analysis] A control-flow analysis must consider where this expression could be invoked and what argument it may receive to determine the possible targets.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-analysis] Techniques such as abstract interpretation, constraint solving, and type systems may be used for control-flow analysis.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] In computer science, a **control-flow graph** (**CFG**) is a representation, using graph notation, of all paths that might be traversed through a function during its execution, or control flow.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The control-flow graph was conceived by Frances E.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Prosser used boolean connectivity matrices for flow analysis before.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The CFG is essential to many compiler optimizations and static-analysis tools.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] A control flow graph is the directed graph of the basic blocks of the function (the nodes of the graph) and the control flow between them (the edges of the graph).
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The exact details vary between representations.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Typically, a basic block consists of a straight-line sequence of instructions or statements.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Only the last instruction or statement in each block can perform control flow, and control flow can only be directed to the first instruction or statement in a block.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] In most CFG representations, there are two specially designated blocks: the *entry block*, through which control enters into the function, and the *exit block*, through which all control exits the function (typically by returning).
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Some representations permit multiple exit blocks, especially if there are different kinds of exit, or permit the exit block to be omitted if it is not reachable .
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] If there is a control-flow edge from block A to block B, then A is called a *predecessor* of B, and B is called a *successor* of A.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The nested structure of the source program makes it a little hard to see the basic blocks.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] As an alternative representation that makes the blocks more obvious, we can flatten that structure into a sequence of labeled blocks.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] To make the control flow explicit, we will require each block to end in either `goto`, an `if`/`else` of `goto`s, or `return` (only in the exit block).
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] This is a source-level representation of the CFG.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The basic blocks consist of sequences of C statements taken directly from the source program.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Only the structured control flow has been eliminated.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] This style of statement-level CFG representation is not commonly used, and it is shown here only for illustrative purposes.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Not all programs can be easily represented this way, even in C.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Notice how the local variable declaration has been raised to the top of function, and its initialization in `block1` has been turned into an assignment.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] This would cause difficulties for scope-driven features such as shadowing and variable-length arrays.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Statements would also need to be significantly rewritten to deal with expression-level control flow, such as is introduced by the `&&`, `||`, and `? :` operators.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Most practical CFG representations use something other than complete source statements as the components of their basic blocks.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] For example, compiler frameworks such as LLVM use a CFG in which basic blocks consist of abstract static single-assignment instructions as their primary IR.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Notice how the block structure is the same in the source-level and the LLVM CFGs.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] In both representations, the functions have the same basic semantics, performing the same sequence of operations and control flow.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Only the representation of the individual operations is different.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] A very explicit control flow graph can be obtained from a source function by placing each statement into its own basic block.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] If the statement is not a control-flow statement, a "fall-through" jump to the block for the next statement is added to the block.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Unfortunately, this tends to create a large number of unnecessary basic blocks and fall-through jumps, which makes subsequent analysis more cumbersome and expensive.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] It is usually desirable that successive statements be placed in the same basic block whenever possible.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] However, this contraction-based algorithm is of little practical importance except as a visualization aid for understanding CFG construction because of the expense of building the initial form.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] In typical implementations, the CFG is built directly from the program in a way that minimizes unnecessary blocks by construction, such as by scanning the program for necessary boundaries between basic blocks.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Reachability is a graph property useful in optimization.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] If a block cannot be reached by any path from the entry block, then it cannot possibly be executed, in which case it is called unreachable code.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Unreachable code can usually be removed from the control flow graph without any negative consequences.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] If the exit block cannot be reached by any path from the entry block, then control flow cannot leave the graph normally.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] This indicates the presence of either an infinite loop or, in representations that directly support these features, an abnormal exit or termination of the program.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The exit block being reachable by some path does not mean that the program will necessarily reach it, and it is impossible to prove that it will be reached in a general graph; see Halting problem.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Optimization can reveal unreachable code and infinite loops that were not apparent in the original program.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] In this form, the loop in this function is not an infinite loop because there is a path which leaves the loop: if `%3` is false, the program will branch to `block3` and return.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] However, a numerical analysis can prove that the product of any number and 2 will be even, which means that `%2` is always zero and `%3` can never be false.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] There is now an infinite loop in the control flow graph, and the exit block can no longer be reached.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Note that this optimization did not change the behavior of the program: it was always true that the loop would never exit.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] All that has changed is that the control flow graph is more accurately reflecting that truth.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] A block M *dominates* a block N if every path from the entry that reaches block N also has to visit block M.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] M is said to *properly dominate* N if M dominates N and they are different blocks.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Furthermore, an individual statement or instruction X is said to properly dominate a statement or instruction Y if the block containing X dominates the block containing Y and, if those are the same block, X strictly precedes Y in the block.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] It is said that a block M *immediately dominates* block N if M dominates N, and there is no intervening block P such that M dominates P and P dominates N.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] In other words, M is the last dominator on all paths from entry to N.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Every reachable block has a unique immediate dominator except for the entry block, which has none.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The *dominator tree* is a directed graph representing the dominance relationships in the function.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The nodes of the graph are the reachable basic blocks of the function, and there is an edge from block M to block N if M is an immediate dominator of N.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Since each non-entry reachable block has a unique immediate dominator, this is a tree rooted at the entry block.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The dominator tree can be calculated efficiently using Lengauer–Tarjan's algorithm.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] In the reverse direction, block M *post-dominates* block N if every path from N to the exit also has to visit block M.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] (This is sometimes written without a hyphen: M *postdominates* N.) The exit block post-dominates all blocks.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] M is said to *properly post-dominate* N if it post-dominates N and they are different blocks.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] M is an *immediate post-dominator* of N if it post-dominates N and there is no block P such that M post-dominates P and P post-dominates N.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Every block from which the exit block is reachable has a unique immediate post-dominator except for the exit block, which has none.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] This gives rise to a *post-dominator tree*, rooted at the exit block, over the blocks from which the exit block is reachable.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The standard definition of dominance includes unreachable blocks, and the standard definition of post-dominance includes blocks from which the exit block cannot be reached.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] However, such blocks have unique properties under these relationships: an unreachable block is dominated by all blocks, and a block from which the exit cannot be reached is post-dominated by all blocks.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Most analyses relying on dominance or post-dominance will want to ignore them, and they are not included in dominator or post-dominator trees.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Some representations require the addition of *impossible edges* to prevent these blocks from existing, at least formally.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] A *critical edge* is an edge which is neither the only edge leaving its source block, nor the only edge entering its destination block.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Some optimizations must *split* critical edges in order to insert instructions along the edge without affecting other paths through the program.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] An edge is split by creating a new block that contains only a jump to the destination block, then replacing the original branch destination with the new block.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] A *retreating edge* is an edge for which there exists a simple path from the entry block to the source block of the edge (such as might be found by a depth-first traversal of the graph) which includes the destination block.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] A retreating edge indicates the presence of a cycle in the control flow graph.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] A retreating edge is called a *back edge* if the destination block is present on all possible paths to the source block, which is to say, if the destination block dominates the source block.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] An *abnormal edge* is an edge whose destination is unknown.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Exception handling constructs can produce them.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] These edges tend to inhibit optimization.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] An *impossible edge* (also known as a *fake edge*) is an edge which cannot actually be traversed during execution and is only added to the graph to preserve some useful property.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] For example, some representations require the addition of impossible edges to ensure that the exit block is always reachable and post-dominates all blocks.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] A strongly-connected component (SCC) of a control flow graph is a set of basic blocks which are all reachable from one another.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The blocks that are part of a loop are always part of the same strongly-connected component.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] A block that is not part of a cycle is always in a strongly-connected component by itself.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] In particular, the entry and exit blocks are always their own strongly-connected components.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The strongly-connected components of a CFG form a directed acyclic graph called the *SCC tree*, where component A has an edge to component B if any block in A has an edge to any block in B.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The SCC tree is isomorphic to the control flow graph if there are no cycles in the CFG; if there is a cycle, the SCC tree essentially collapses all blocks and edges in it into a single node.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] This can be useful for analyses that wish to treat all of the blocks in a cycle as equivalent.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] For example, when trying to find an object lifetime that covers a set of use-points as narrowly as possible, if one of those use-points is within a cyclic SCC, the lifetime must fully cover every block in that component.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] A *loop header* (sometimes called the *entry point* of the loop) is a dominator that is the target of a loop-forming back edge.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The loop header dominates all blocks in the loop body.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] A block may be a loop header for more than one loop.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] A loop may have multiple entry points, in which case it has no "loop header".
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Suppose block M is a dominator with several incoming edges, some of them being back edges (so M is a loop header).
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] It is advantageous to several optimization passes to break M up into two blocks Mpre and Mloop.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The contents of M and back edges are moved to Mloop, the rest of the edges are moved to point into Mpre, and a new edge from Mpre to Mloop is inserted (so that Mpre is the immediate dominator of Mloop).
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] In the beginning, Mpre would be empty, but passes like loop-invariant code motion could populate it.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Mpre is called the *loop pre-header*, and Mloop would be the loop header.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] A control flow graph is called *reducible* if all its retreating edges are back edges.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The other edges in such a CFG are called *forward edges*.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The forward edges form a directed acyclic graph, and the back edges always lead to a basic block that control flow has already passed through.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Reducible CFGs generally have stronger static properties and can be more easily analyzed and optimized.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] For example, many loop optimizations are designed to work only on reducible CFGs.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Structured programming languages are often designed such that all CFGs they produce are reducible, and common structured programming statements such as IF, FOR, WHILE, BREAK, and CONTINUE reliably produce reducible graphs.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] To directly produce an irreducible graph, statements such as GOTO are needed that can jump to an arbitrary point in the program, although not all uses of GOTO produce irreducible CFGs.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Irreducible CFGs can also be produced by some compiler optimizations, such as jump threading.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Irreducible CFGs can be converted to reducible CFGs, but this often requires duplicating code or introducing new variables to the program.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The loop connectedness of a CFG is defined with respect to a given depth-first search tree (DFST) of the CFG.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] This DFST should be rooted at the start node and cover every node of the CFG.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] In this context, edges in the CFG which run from a node to one of its DFST ancestors (including itself) are called back edges.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] This does not necessarily coincide with the usual definition of a back edge because a DFST ancestor need not dominate the source node of the edge.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] The loop connectedness is the largest number of back edges found in any cycle-free path of the CFG.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] In a reducible CFG, the loop connectedness is independent of the DFST chosen.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] Loop connectedness has been used to reason about the time complexity of data-flow analysis.
[src:control-flow-analysis/control-flow-graph] While control-flow graphs represent the control flow of a single procedure, inter-procedural control-flow graphs represent the control flow of whole programs.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] In computing, **inline expansion**, or **inlining**, is a manual or compiler optimization that replaces a function call site with the body of the called function.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Inline expansion is similar to macro expansion, but occurs during compiling, without changing the source code (the text), while macro expansion occurs before compiling, and results in different text that is then processed by the compiler.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Inlining is an important optimization, but has complex effects on performance.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] As a rule of thumb, some inlining will improve speed at very minor cost of space, but excess inlining will hurt speed, due to inlined code consuming too much of the instruction cache, and also cost significant space.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] A survey of the modest academic literature on inlining from the 1980s and 1990s is given in Peyton Jones & Marlow 1999.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Inline expansion is similar to macro expansion as the compiler places a new copy of the function in each place it is called.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Inlined functions run a little faster than the normal functions as function-calling-overheads are saved, however, there is a memory penalty.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] If a function is inlined 10 times, there will be 10 copies of the function inserted into the code.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Hence inlining is best for small functions that are called often.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] In C++ the member functions of a class, if defined within the class definition, are inlined by default (no need to use the *inline* reserved word (keyword)); otherwise, the keyword is needed.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] The compiler may ignore the programmer’s attempt to inline a function, mainly if it is particularly large.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Inline expansion is used to eliminate the time overhead (excess time) when a function is called.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] It is typically used for functions that execute frequently.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] It also has a space benefit for very small functions, and is an enabling transformation for other optimizations.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Without inline functions, the compiler decides which functions to inline.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] The programmer has little or no control over which functions are inlined and which are not.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Giving this degree of control to the programmer allows for the use of application-specific knowledge in choosing which functions to inline.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Ordinarily, when a function is invoked, control is transferred to its definition by a branch or call instruction.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] With inlining, control drops through directly to the code for the function, without a branch or call instruction.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Compilers usually implement statements with inlining.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Loop conditions and loop bodies need lazy evaluation.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] This property is fulfilled when the code to compute loop conditions and loop bodies is inlined.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Performance considerations are another reason to inline statements.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] In the context of functional programming languages, inline expansion is usually followed by the beta-reduction transformation.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] A programmer might inline a function manually through copy-and-paste programming, as a one-time operation on the source code.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] However, other methods of controlling inlining (see below) are preferable, because they do not precipitate bugs arising when the programmer overlooks a (possibly modified) duplicated version of the original function body, while fixing a bug in the inlined function.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] The direct effect of this optimization is to improve time performance (by eliminating call overhead), at the cost of worsening space usage (due to duplicating the function body).
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] The code expansion due to duplicating the function body dominates, except for simple cases, and thus the direct effect of inline expansion is to improve time at the cost of space.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] However, the main benefit of inline expansion is to allow further optimizations and improved scheduling, due to increasing the size of the function body, as better optimization is possible on larger functions.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] The impact of inlining varies by programming language and program, due to different degrees of abstraction.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] The main benefit of inlining, however, is the further optimizations it allows.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Optimizations that cross function boundaries can be done without requiring interprocedural optimization (IPO): once inlining has been performed, added *intra*procedural optimizations ("global optimizations") become possible on the enlarged function body.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Conversely, in some cases a language specification may allow a program to make added assumptions about arguments to procedures that it can no longer make after the procedure is inlined, preventing some optimizations.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Smarter compilers (such as Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC)) will track this, but naive inlining loses this information.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] The direct cost of inlining is increased code size, due to duplicating the function body at each call site.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Thus inlining may be minimized or eliminated if optimizing for code size, as is often the case in embedded systems.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Inlining also imposes a cost on performance, due to the code expansion (due to duplication) hurting instruction cache performance.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] This is most significant if, before expansion, the working set of the program (or a hot section of code) fit in one level of the memory hierarchy (e.g., L1 cache), but after expansion it no longer fits, resulting in frequent cache misses at that level.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Due to the significant difference in performance at different levels of the hierarchy, this hurts performance considerably.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] At the highest level this can result in increased page faults, catastrophic performance degradation due to thrashing, or the program failing to run at all.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] This last is rare in common desktop and server applications, where code size is small relative to available memory, but can be an issue for resource-constrained environments such as embedded systems.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] One way to mitigate this problem is to split functions into a smaller hot inline path (fast path), and a larger cold non-inline path (slow path).
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] This is a similar issue to other code expanding optimizations such as loop unrolling, which also reduces number of instructions processed, but can decrease performance due to poorer cache performance.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] The precise effect of inlining on cache performance is complex.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] For small cache sizes (much smaller than the working set before expansion), the increased sequentiality dominates, and inlining improves cache performance.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] For cache sizes close to the working set, where inlining expands the working set so it no longer fits in cache, this dominates and cache performance decreases.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] For cache sizes larger than the working set, inlining has negligible impact on cache performance.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Further, changes in cache design, such as load forwarding, can offset the increase in cache misses.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Compilers use a variety of mechanisms to decide which function calls should be inlined; these can include manual hints from programmers for specific functions, together with overall control via command-line options.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Inlining is done automatically by many compilers in many languages, based on judgment of whether inlining is beneficial, while in other cases it can be manually specified via compiler directives, typically using a keyword or compiler directive called `inline`.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Typically this only hints that inlining is desired, rather than requiring inlining, with the force of the hint varying by language and compiler.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Typically, compiler developers keep the above performance issues in mind, and incorporate heuristics into their compilers that choose which functions to inline so as to improve performance, rather than worsening it, in most cases.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Once the compiler has decided to inline a particular function, performing the inlining operation itself is usually simple.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Depending on whether a compiler inlines functions across code in different languages, the compiler can inline on either a high-level intermediate representation (like abstract syntax trees) or a low-level intermediate representation.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] In either case, the compiler simply computes the arguments, stores them in variables corresponding to the function's arguments, and then inserts the body of the function at the call site.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] When a linker inlines functions, it may inline functions whose source is not available, such as library functions (see link-time optimization).
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] A runtime system can inline a function also.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Runtime inlining can use dynamic profiling information to make better decisions about which functions to inline, as in the Java HotSpot compiler.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] In an actual C application, it would be preferable to use an inlining language feature such as parameterized macros or inline functions to tell the compiler to transform the code in this way.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] The next section lists ways to optimize this code.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Assembler macros provide an alternative approach to inlining whereby a sequence of instructions can normally be generated inline by macro expansion from a single macro source statement (with zero or more parameters).
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] One of the parameters might be an option to alternatively generate a one-time separate subroutine containing the sequence and processed instead by an inlined call to the function.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] A range of different heuristics have been explored for inlining.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Usually, an inlining algorithm has a certain code budget (an allowed increase in program size) and aims to inline the most valuable callsites without exceeding that budget.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] In this sense, many inlining algorithms are usually modeled after the Knapsack problem.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] To decide which callsites are more valuable, an inlining algorithm must estimate their benefit—i.e. the expected decrease in the execution time.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Commonly, inliners use profiling information about the frequency of the execution of different code paths to estimate the benefits.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Inline expansion itself is an optimization, since it eliminates overhead from calls, but it is much more important as an enabling transformation.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] That is, once the compiler expands a function body in the context of its call site—often with arguments that may be fixed constants—it may be able to do a variety of transformations that were not possible before.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] For example, a conditional branch may turn out to be always true or always false at this particular call site.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] This in turn may enable dead code elimination, loop-invariant code motion, or induction variable elimination.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] In the C example in the prior section, optimizing opportunities abound.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Complete inline expansion is not always possible, due to recursion: recursively inline expanding the calls will not terminate.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] There are various solutions, such as expanding a bounded amount, or analyzing the call graph and breaking loops at certain nodes (i.e., not expanding some edge in a recursive loop).
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] An identical problem occurs in macro expansion, as recursive expansion does not terminate, and is typically resolved by forbidding recursive macros (as in C and C++).
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Traditionally, in languages such as C, inline expansion was accomplished at the source level using parameterized macros.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Many compilers can also inline expand some recursive functions; recursive macros are typically illegal.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Bjarne Stroustrup, the designer of C++, likes to emphasize that macros should be avoided wherever possible, and advocates extensive use of inline functions.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Many compilers aggressively inline functions wherever it is beneficial to do so.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Although it can lead to larger executables, aggressive inlining has nevertheless become more and more desirable as memory capacity has increased faster than CPU speed.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Inlining is a critical optimization in languages for functional and object-oriented programming, which rely on it to provide enough context for their typically small functions to make classical optimizations effective.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Many languages, including Java and functional languages, do not provide language constructs for inline functions, but their compilers or interpreters often perform aggressive inline expansion.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Other languages provide constructs for explicit hints, generally as compiler directives (pragmas).
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] The language Ada has a pragma for inline functions.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] C and C++ have an `inline` keyword which serves as a hint that inlining may be beneficial; however, in newer versions, its main purpose is instead to alter the visibility and linking behavior of the function.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] In C++, a method of a class that is defined inside the class body will implicitly be inlined.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] In Kotlin, an `inline` function will be inlined, and can be signaled not to be inlined using `noinline`.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] `inline` copies the function bytecode into the call site, inlines lambda arguments, and eliminates function call and lambda allocation overhead.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] In equivalent Java (or Java bytecode), the function will be represented as logic at the call site.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] In Rust, inlining is automatically done by the compiler.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] Rust provides an `#[inline]` attribute that suggests to the compiler that a function should be inlined, but does not guarantee it; the compiler may ignore even `#[inline(always)]`.
[src:control-flow-analysis/function-inlining] In debug mode, the compiler will never inline.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] IPO seeks to reduce or eliminate duplicate calculations and inefficient use of memory and to simplify iterative sequences such as loops.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] If a call to another routine occurs within a loop, IPO analysis may determine that it is best to inline that routine.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] Additionally, IPO may re-order the routines for better memory layout and locality.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] IPO may also include typical compiler optimizations applied on a whole-program level, for example, dead code elimination (DCE), which removes code that is never executed.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] IPO also tries to ensure better use of constants.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] Modern compilers offer IPO as an option at compile-time.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] The actual IPO process may occur at any step between the human-readable source code and producing a finished executable binary program.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] For languages that compile on a file-by-file basis, effective IPO across translation units (module files) requires knowledge of the "entry points" of the program so that a **whole program optimization** (**WPO**) can be run.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] In many cases, this is implemented as a **link-time optimization** (**LTO**) pass, because the whole program is visible to the linker.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] The objective of any optimization for speed is to have the program run as swiftly as possible; the problem is that it is not possible for a compiler to correctly analyze a program and determine what it *will* do, much less what the programmer *intended* for it to do.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] By contrast, human programmers start at the other end with a purpose and attempt to produce a program that will achieve it, preferably without expending a lot of thought in the process.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] For various reasons, including readability, programs are frequently broken up into a number of procedures that handle a few general cases.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] However, the generality of each procedure may result in wasted effort in specific usages.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] Interprocedural optimization represents an attempt at reducing this waste.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] Suppose there is a procedure that evaluates `f(x)`, and that `f` is a pure function, and the code requests the result of `f(6)` and then later, `f(6)` again.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] This second evaluation is almost certainly unnecessary: the result could have instead been saved and referred to later.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] Losing these side effects via non-evaluation a second time may be acceptable, or they may not.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] More generally, aside from optimization, the second reason to use procedures is to avoid duplication of code that would produce the same results, or almost the same results, each time the procedure is performed.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] A general approach to optimization would therefore be to reverse this: some or all invocations of a certain procedure are replaced by the respective code, with the parameters appropriately substituted.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] The compiler will then try to optimize the result.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] Once all files have been compiled separately into object files, traditionally, a compiler links (merges) the object files into a single file, the executable.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] However, in LTO as implemented by the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) and LLVM, the compiler is able to dump its intermediate representation (IR), i.e.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] GIMPLE bytecode or LLVM bitcode, respectively, so that all the different compilation units that will go to make up a single executable can be optimized as a single module when the link finally happens.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] This expands the scope of interprocedural optimizations to encompass the whole program (or, rather, everything that is visible at link time).
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] With link-time optimization, the compiler can apply various forms of interprocedural optimization to the whole program, allowing for deeper analysis, more optimization, and ultimately better program performance.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] In practice, LTO does not always optimize the entire program—library functions, especially dynamically linked shared objects, are intentionally kept out to avoid excessive duplication and to allow for updating.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] Static linking does naturally lend to the concept of LTO, but it only works with library archives that contain IR objects as opposed to machine-code only object files.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] Due to performance concerns, not even the entire unit is always directly used—a program could be partitioned in a divide-and-conquer style LTO such as GCC's WHOPR.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] And of course, when the program being built is itself a library, the optimization would keep every externally-available (exported) symbol, without trying too hard at removing them as a part of DCE.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] A much more limited form of WPO is still possible without LTO, as exemplified by GCC's `-fwhole-program` switch.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] This mode makes GCC assume that the module being compiled contains the entry point of the entire program, so that every other function in it is not externally used and can be safely optimized away.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] Since it only applies to a single module, it cannot truly encompass the whole program.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] It can be combined with LTO in the one-big-module sense, which is useful when the linker is not communicating back to GCC about what entry points or symbols are being used externally.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] For procedural languages like ALGOL, interprocedural analysis and optimization appear to have entered commercial practice in the early 1970s.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] IBM's PL/I Optimizing Compiler performed interprocedural analysis to understand the side effects of both procedure calls and exceptions (cast, in PL/I terms as "on conditions") and in papers by Fran Allen.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] Work on compilation of the APL programming language was necessarily interprocedural.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] The techniques of interprocedural analysis and optimization were the subject of academic research in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] They re-emerged into the commercial compiler world in the early 1990s with compilers from both Convex Computer Corporation (the "Application Compiler" for the Convex C4) and from Ardent (the compiler for the Ardent Titan).
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] These compilers demonstrated that the technologies could be made sufficiently fast to be acceptable in a commercial compiler; subsequently interprocedural techniques have appeared in a number of commercial and non-commercial systems.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] The GNU Compiler Collection has function inlining at all optimization levels.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] At `-O1` this only applies to those only called once (`-finline-functions-once`), at `-O2` this constraint is relaxed (`-finline-functions`).
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] By default this is a single-file-only behavior, but with link-time optimization `-flto` it becomes whole program.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] Clang's command-line interface is similar to that of GCC, with the exception that there is no `-fwhole-program` option.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] Object files produced by LTO contain a compiler-specific intermediate representation (IR) that is interpreted at link-time.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] To make sure this plays well with static libraries, newer GNU linkers have a "linker plugin" interface that allows the compiler to convert the object files into a machine code form when needed.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] This plugin also helps drive the LTO process in general.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] Alternatively, a "fat LTO" object can be produced to contain both machine code and the IR, but this takes more space.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] Since both GCC and LLVM (clang) are able produce an IR from a variety of programming languages, link-time IPO can happen even across language boundaries.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] This is most commonly demonstrated with C and C++, but LLVM makes it possible for Rust and all other LLVM-based compilers too.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] GCC and Clang perform IPO by default at optimization level 2.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] However, the degree of optimization is limited when LTO is disabled, as IPO can only happen within an object file and non-static functions can never be eliminated.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] The latter problem has a non-LTO solution: the `-fwhole-program` switch can be used to assume that only `main()` is non-static, i.e. visible from the outside.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] Another non-LTO technique is "function sections" (`-ffunction-sections` in GCC and Clang).
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] By placing each function into its own section in the object file, the linker can perform dead code removal without an IR by removing unreferenced sections (using the linker option `--gc-sections`).
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] A similar option is available for variables, but it causes much worse code to be produced.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] The Intel C/C++ compilers allow whole-program IPO.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] The flag to enable interprocedural optimizations for a single file is `-ip`, the flag to enable interprocedural optimization across all files in the program is `-ipo`.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] The MSVC compiler, integrated into Visual Studio, also supports interprocedural optimization on the whole program.
[src:control-flow-analysis/interprocedural-optimization] A compiler-independent interface for enabling whole-program interprocedural optimizations is via the `INTERPROCEDURAL_OPTIMIZATION` property in CMake.
